                <head>198. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On February 6, 1967, Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName>
                    arrived in London for a week’s visit, during which he and British Prime Minister
                        <persName>Harold Wilson</persName> sought unsuccessfully to initiate peace
                    negotiations between the United States and the Democratic Republic of North
                    Vietnam. Documentation on Sunflower, as the initiative was code-named, is
                    printed in <ref target="frus1964-68v05">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1964–1968, volume V</ref>. Memoirs
                    by participants in the initiative include <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Lyndon
                        Johnson</persName>’s <hi rend="italic">The Vantage Point,</hi> pages
                    253–255; <persName>Harold Wilson</persName>’s <hi rend="italic">The Labour
                        Government,</hi> 1964–1970, page 442; and <persName>Chester
                        Cooper</persName>’s <hi rend="italic">The Lost Crusade,</hi> pages
                    350–368.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
